300
00:41:02.984 --> 00:41:13.013
Incoming livestream: I want to define what we're even aiming for. So, AI native gets thrown around a lot, it means a lot of different things to different people, and the way I think about it is that there are basically three levels. Most companies are at level 1.


301
00:41:13.254 --> 00:41:24.103
Incoming livestream: AI-assisted is where everyone starts. You give people ChatGPT, they draft emails, generate boilerplate, you know, the organization doesn't change, the workflows don't change, you just do the same things a little faster.


302
00:41:24.194 --> 00:41:36.164
Incoming livestream: Ai augmented is where things start to get interesting. That's where you start slowly, incrementally redesigning workflows. You're not just using AI as a tool, but you're putting agents in the loop. You're changing how work actually flows.


303
00:41:36.204 --> 00:41:49.614
Incoming livestream: And maybe the AI does the first pass on your code review, and then the human does the second. So the process is slightly different. And then finally, AI Native is where you get to a structural shift. This is where you've designed the organization from the ground up.


304
00:41:49.614 --> 00:42:02.863
Incoming livestream: Assuming AI is a co-participant in the work. It's not a tool, it's a teammate. And that's your knowledge management, your delivery model, your expertise, all of them have to be designed to be consumed and amplified by agents.


305
00:42:02.924 --> 00:42:07.733
Incoming livestream: So at Trail of Bits, what this means is that our security expertise should compound


306
00:42:07.794 --> 00:42:25.074
Incoming livestream: with code. Every engagement we do, all the skills, all the workflows we build make the next engagement faster. Every engineer operates with an arsenal of specialized agents built from our 14 years of audit knowledge. That's not we use AI, that's AI is on the team.


307
00:42:26.974 --> 00:42:41.473
Incoming livestream: So, candidly, I had a lot of trouble getting here. When I first launched this initiative inside Trail of Bits, there was an incredible amount of pushback. Like you would not believe. I think that I had about 5% of the company with me, about 95% against.


308
00:42:41.634 --> 00:42:52.193
Incoming livestream: At least 50% were passively resisting. There were probably a good quarter that were actively resisting. I'm sure people thought about quitting. Just totally, like, cars on the table here.


309
00:42:52.224 --> 00:43:01.594
Incoming livestream: And this isn't really an uncommon issue. Whenever new technology comes around, people resist adopting it, and it can be the most senior, most expert people that resist the most.


310
00:43:01.594 --> 00:43:12.374
Incoming livestream: So I had to work through a couple of common psychological barriers that are well documented in research, and build systems that worked within those psychological conditions to get to success.


311
00:43:12.564 --> 00:43:17.164
Incoming livestream: The core insight here is the problem's not the technology, it's the people.


312
00:43:17.554 --> 00:43:22.234
Incoming livestream: So, these are four, psychological barriers.


313
00:43:22.464 --> 00:43:36.113
Incoming livestream: that, that are, I think, key among all the other ones in getting people to adopt new technology inside of a company like Trailabits. First was self-enhancing bias. This is the tendency to perceive oneself in an overly favorable manner.


314
00:43:36.114 --> 00:43:44.303
Incoming livestream: So you obviously want to maintain your own self-esteem, and this bias means that you take credit for your success, and you blame external factors on failures.


315
00:43:44.414 --> 00:43:57.284
Incoming livestream: Now there are some funny interactions with this, like, in some research by Paul Meehl and Robin Dawes, you can take the variables an expert says they use and build a crude, linear model, and the model outperforms the expert.


316
00:43:57.634 --> 00:44:08.614
Incoming livestream: Almost always. And it's not because the model is smarter, it's because it's consistent. Humans don't operate the same every day. Some of you are very hungover right now, and I'm sure you could agree with me on this.


317
00:44:09.114 --> 00:44:16.644
Incoming livestream: And this gets worse with seniority. The more that you are an expert, the more that you believe that your intuition is what got you there.


318
00:44:16.844 --> 00:44:27.783
Incoming livestream: There's also an identity threat. This really attacks the core of who we are, that, like, I spent 20 years doing this, a machine can't… can't do 20 years of experience and, like, get to be me.


319
00:44:28.034 --> 00:44:44.443
Incoming livestream: And this shows up in things like, there was… Stanford ran a cooking study. They used this device, some cooking system, and they advertised it two different ways. One way is it does the cooking for you. The other way is it helps you cook better. And, it's the same device.


320
00:44:44.584 --> 00:44:50.503
Incoming livestream: But for people who identify as cooks, they reject the device if it's advertised the first way.


321
00:44:50.644 --> 00:44:52.883
Incoming livestream: There's another dimension to this as well.


322
00:44:52.914 --> 00:45:12.173
Incoming livestream: based on the symbolism of what the activity represents. So, for instance, if you had a tattoo robot, people do not want tattoo… do not want robots to give them tattoos, because it's symbolic. There's a human craft to it. But they're fine with a tattoo removing one, because that's an instrumental process, there's no symbolism there.


323
00:45:12.174 --> 00:45:15.814
Incoming livestream: So for us, security auditing is deeply symbolic work.


324
00:45:15.964 --> 00:45:22.694
Incoming livestream: And it's important to frame the AI as making you a more dangerous auditor, not something that does the audit.


325
00:45:23.614 --> 00:45:40.794
Incoming livestream: There's also challenges in opacity. So in this case, the subjective understanding of human judgment is high, and AI judgment is low, but objectively, you actually understand neither. Like when a doctor tries to communicate to you that you might have some medical condition or cancer or something.


326
00:45:41.124 --> 00:45:46.554
Incoming livestream: You might think you understand the words that are coming out of their mouth, but you absolutely do not.


327
00:45:47.014 --> 00:46:01.844
Incoming livestream: But the level of trust you have with the doctor is way higher than if a machine just prints out a receipt and says, here's what you got. So the way you typically fix this is, you could modify the same AI to show you, well, why is this not a benign…


328
00:46:01.864 --> 00:46:26.843
Incoming livestream: skin condition. And if you give a visual comparison to a benign mole, then trust starts to equalize. So we had to think about how to build this into our process as well. And then finally, humans have an intolerance for imperfection. So again, well-known academic study, participants watch an algorithm outperform a human forecaster, the algorithm is better. But the second that the algorithm makes a single error, humans switch back


329
00:46:26.844 --> 00:46:28.194
Incoming livestream: Back to preferring the human.


330
00:46:28.724 --> 00:46:37.114
Incoming livestream: The fix, in this case, is generally to let people modify the algorithm. If they have the perception of control, then they start to trust the process again.


331
00:46:38.064 --> 00:46:39.854
Incoming livestream: So what did we do?


332
00:46:40.484 --> 00:46:59.213
Incoming livestream: So for the self-enhancing bias, we built a maturity matrix. This was controversial internally, nobody likes being told they're at level 1, but that's the point. You can't argue with something that you're… you can't argue that you're good enough when there's a visible ladder, and it also makes the conversation concrete instead of, I don't think AI is useful.


333
00:46:59.604 --> 00:47:07.543
Incoming livestream: It also creates social proof. When you see your peers escalating up the ladder, the passive 50% of the company starts to move with them.


334
00:47:07.754 --> 00:47:10.333
Incoming livestream: The identity threat was extremely difficult.


335
00:47:10.694 --> 00:47:27.344
Incoming livestream: You had to get people to accept skill-allowing automations and reject skill-replacing automation. Same tool, different framing. So we never really asked anyone… well, not never really… we didn't ever ask anyone to stop being a security expert, but we gave them a different way to express that identity.


336
00:47:27.344 --> 00:47:39.153
Incoming livestream: So the skills repos that I hope you all are familiar with are the clearest example of that. When we have a senior consultant on the team write a constant time analysis skill.


337
00:47:39.154 --> 00:47:50.653
Incoming livestream: They're not being replaced, they're becoming permanent inside the company. And that means their expertise is encoded and reusable by the whole team. That's an identity upgrade, not a threat.


338
00:47:51.024 --> 00:48:05.134
Incoming livestream: So, the maturity matrix reinforces this. Level 3 isn't who uses AI the most, it's who invents new ways and builds new tools. So the identity shifts from, I don't need AI, to, I'm the one who makes AI dangerous.


339
00:48:05.544 --> 00:48:12.883
Incoming livestream: We also did hackathons instead of mandates. I never forced anyone to adopt these tools, but we created a space where people could experiment on their own terms.


340
00:48:14.194 --> 00:48:15.973
Incoming livestream: I'm not doing that. There we go.


341
00:48:17.824 --> 00:48:24.123
Incoming livestream: For the intolerance for imperfection, everyone… if somebody's first experience with AI is bad, you've lost them for months.


342
00:48:24.174 --> 00:48:40.363
Incoming livestream: So, one error, and people just abandoned the system. So we invested a lot in ways to reduce the ways that AI can fail, embarrassingly. We curated a marketplace so that people weren't getting random plugins. We created sandboxing tools so clawed Code didn't accidentally delete your work.


343
00:48:40.414 --> 00:48:50.754
Incoming livestream: We put guardrails and foot gun reduction systems in place so that there were a lot less of, like, you know, AI did something stupid stories circulating in Slack.


344
00:48:51.424 --> 00:49:04.103
Incoming livestream: For opacity, we clearly articulated what tools were allowed and which ones were not, and under what conditions. We described those conditions and why we decided to, adopt those risk levels.


345
00:49:04.294 --> 00:49:14.714
Incoming livestream: And then we made adoption fast and visible. So this really underpins everything else. If the setup takes an hour, and the first result is mediocre, then you've confirmed everyone's priors.


346
00:49:15.154 --> 00:49:24.544
Incoming livestream: So we have copy-pasteable configurations, one-command setup, we have a standardized toolchain, and the first experience is fast and good. And then I think, finally.


347
00:49:25.024 --> 00:49:41.784
Incoming livestream: I matter to this more than most people think. The passive 50% of the company is gonna watch what leadership actually does, not what it says. So, if I'm using these tools visibly every single day, it signals that it's not a fad. We're actually all in.


348
00:49:42.794 --> 00:49:49.584
Incoming livestream: So that's the problem and the approach. Here's the actual system we built. So, five parts, each one addresses barriers we just talked about.


349
00:49:49.654 --> 00:49:58.644
Incoming livestream: I'm gonna walk through each of these in detail with screenshots and examples, but this is the overview. You could think of it like a checklist, but you need all five for it to compound.


350
00:49:58.644 --> 00:50:17.344
Incoming livestream: And, importantly, this isn't, like, some strategy deck that, like, I'm presenting here. This is everything that we built ourselves, and most of it has been open-sourced so that all of you can use it right now. This is what I use for a 140-person company doing real client work. So let's go through each one.


351
00:50:18.454 --> 00:50:29.813
Incoming livestream: First one, super boring. We had to standardize. We got everybody on Clawed code, and we treat it like any other enterprise tool. We have supported configs, no good defaults, and a clear path to, this is how we do it here.


352
00:50:29.814 --> 00:50:38.763
Incoming livestream: If you skip this step, you can't build anything else, because you end up with 40 different workflows and zero leverage on it. So, for better or for worse, we settled on Clawed code.


353
00:50:39.414 --> 00:50:41.824
Incoming livestream: I think it was for better.


354
00:50:42.114 --> 00:50:54.014
Incoming livestream: Next thing, we wrote an AI handbook. And this wasn't to teach people how to prompt, but it was to remove ambiguity. What tools are approved and what isn't, especially for sensitive data, where we have a lot of that.


355
00:50:54.104 --> 00:51:02.574
Incoming livestream: So we explicitly call things out, like where a tool can't be used on client code, where meeting recorders are disallowed depending on engagement type.


356
00:51:02.574 --> 00:51:26.204
Incoming livestream: Where we want people to use a specific alternative, and that stops the endless Slack debates. It gives project managers and engineers a shared answer, and it makes client conversations consistent. When we have highly sensitive clients ask us questions about, hey, what are you using on the code that I've given you? I can give them a clear answer that everybody knows. So once you have a policy, you can push harder on adoption.


357
00:51:27.454 --> 00:51:31.474
Incoming livestream: Then, I will… I will post this on Twitter, because no one can read it.


358
00:51:31.594 --> 00:51:43.464
Incoming livestream: But we built an AI maturity matrix. This makes AI a first-class professional capability. It's just the same as you can use Git, or you can write tests, or you can audit C.


359
00:51:43.474 --> 00:51:51.653
Incoming livestream: It's not a vibe, it's a ladder. So there are clear levels, there are expectations for getting one… for, escalating.


360
00:51:51.664 --> 00:52:01.903
Incoming livestream: And there are consequences for staying stuck. It starts at level 0, and if you're stuck at level zero, and you're not engaged in this process, then there may be…


361
00:52:02.044 --> 00:52:04.274
Incoming livestream: Transition out of the company.


362
00:52:04.754 --> 00:52:23.563
Incoming livestream: And this is how you avoid two different failure modes. You don't want leadership to, like, wish adoption into existence, and you don't want the organization splitting into AI people versus everybody else. This is a whole company need. Everybody needs to be on board. So this turns it into a normal part of performance, growth, resource allocation.


363
00:52:23.644 --> 00:52:25.493
Incoming livestream: And, and bonuses.


364
00:52:27.814 --> 00:52:33.034
Incoming livestream: Now the fun part. So, hackathons. Hackathons became a management system for us.


365
00:52:33.174 --> 00:52:45.664
Incoming livestream: We run short, focused sprints, 2-3 days, with a specific objective, one objective, and that's how we keep pace when the ecosystem changes every single week. So here's one of the kickoffs for one of them,


366
00:52:45.754 --> 00:52:54.014
Incoming livestream: We did this one, or actually, well, these are both… these are the last two, I think. Which one? I think the one on the right.


367
00:52:54.344 --> 00:53:13.474
Incoming livestream: is, our autonomy-focused one. The most important thing is that we put a constraint on the hackathon. You had to run clawed code and bypass permissions mode. This was to break the barrier on people's hesitance to giving full control over the tools and build systems that allow it to work under those constraints.


368
00:53:13.574 --> 00:53:21.864
Incoming livestream: So that was intentional. It forces everyone to learn how to use sandboxing, guardrails, and how to structure their work so that the agents can succeed on their own.


369
00:53:23.154 --> 00:53:30.433
Incoming livestream: Other design choices that we made, we focus on public repositories so that we can move fast and show real outcomes.


370
00:53:31.084 --> 00:53:41.223
Incoming livestream: We measured success on activity. I wanted people to put in the reps. So, we're talking about issues fixed and filed, PRs reviewed and merged, branches created and deleted.


371
00:53:41.354 --> 00:53:48.264
Incoming livestream: We're not so worried about, like, the meaning behind all that code. I just want activities that they put in the reps.


372
00:53:48.584 --> 00:53:52.474
Incoming livestream: And then we had people work in pairs. Every change gets reviewed by a buddy.


373
00:53:52.844 --> 00:54:04.704
Incoming livestream: So even with the move fast, sort of sprint-style work, we had some quality control built in. So the hackathons create motion, but the motion doesn't compound unless you capture it.


374
00:54:05.634 --> 00:54:10.133
Incoming livestream: And that's where we started collecting these artifacts as skills.


375
00:54:10.544 --> 00:54:24.023
Incoming livestream: So a skill, most of you know, is a reusable structured workflow, usually with examples, constraints, and a way to verify the output. So we maintain 3 separate skills repos, two of which you all have access to.


376
00:54:24.024 --> 00:54:32.774
Incoming livestream: We have an internal one that has a lot of company-specific workflows and a lot of our most sensitive vulnerability research-related skills, but we also have an external one.


377
00:54:32.774 --> 00:54:38.843
Incoming livestream: So that the broader community can validate and improve on the work that we're doing.


378
00:54:38.854 --> 00:54:43.784
Incoming livestream: The third one is we have a curated marketplace, which I think I'm talking about next, yeah?


379
00:54:44.064 --> 00:55:02.874
Incoming livestream: So for a firm like ours, I appreciate the external validation. It keeps us honest, and it forces us to write things that other people can actually use. That's a core value of Trail of Bits. I don't want to just release a black hat talk that gets me a wired article or whatever and disappear the next day. We measure success based on


380
00:55:03.124 --> 00:55:09.573
Incoming livestream: downloads of a specific tool, or stars of a specific tool. I want continued usage,


381
00:55:09.764 --> 00:55:11.534
Incoming livestream: And, and enhancement.


382
00:55:13.054 --> 00:55:27.044
Incoming livestream: So then, we have another problem. You know, you tell people to go use skills and plugins, and they go use skills and plugins, and they get a whole bunch of random stuff that's, like, AI slop, filled with emojis, and, you know, steals your cryptocurrency.


383
00:55:27.274 --> 00:55:47.093
Incoming livestream: So we created a curated marketplace, and this is just standard, you know, enterprise stuff, right? We made a known good place for third-party skills. You want a third-party skill? There's a command built into the curated marketplace that goes out and grabs it from somewhere else, filters it, and then puts it into ours. So if you want adoption, you need a safe supply chain.


384
00:55:48.094 --> 00:55:49.683
Incoming livestream: Basic enterprise thinking.


385
00:55:51.054 --> 00:56:09.594
Incoming livestream: Then we made the defaults dead simple. So after we went through a couple of rounds of this, we started to get to, really, like, known-good, Trail-A-Bits-style Cloud Code installation. So we publish a repository that has our recommended Cloud Code configuration. I want to eliminate tribal knowledge.


386
00:56:09.594 --> 00:56:24.084
Incoming livestream: We want to have specifics around, this is how we do Claude code at Trail of Bits. So we put known good settings, a known good claud.md, and anything else that we want to standardize for how people use it. We also included some usage instructions there.


387
00:56:24.294 --> 00:56:38.033
Incoming livestream: Now, this is freely available, but there is a whole separate section that describes how to use it for bug hunting that we're keeping internal, so if you're wondering where that part is, that's why it's missing. So it's very developer-focused.


388
00:56:39.764 --> 00:56:44.324
Incoming livestream: Then the real constraint, obviously. The more control that you give to these agents.


389
00:56:44.574 --> 00:56:53.913
Incoming livestream: You're gonna want a sandbox. So we give people choices. We don't just tell people to do one thing, or enforce the Claude built-in sandbox, which is quite good.


390
00:56:53.944 --> 00:57:07.623
Incoming livestream: But we give people choices, and we invested in building some of our own. We built a dev container option. We made, another one that, automatically interacts with DigitalOcean to create single-use virtual machines in the cloud.


391
00:57:07.684 --> 00:57:17.654
Incoming livestream: And then we documented the native macOS sandboxing option. So the point wasn't that everybody uses the same sandbox, the point is that everyone has a safe sandbox to use.


392
00:57:17.654 --> 00:57:29.203
Incoming livestream: You know, we have a variety of different things going under one roof at Trail of Bits. We have engineering engagements, research engagements, audits, we have non-technical staff, operations staff, and they all need different solutions. I can't mandate one.


393
00:57:30.994 --> 00:57:41.334
Incoming livestream: Then, as you give people more autonomy, these agents start to go haywire in different ways. They start to pull in third-party dependencies that have security issues.


394
00:57:41.334 --> 00:57:54.563
Incoming livestream: So, the one step that we took that I think, is extraordinarily effective, besides the ignore scripts in NPM, was implement a mandatory developer, mandatory package cool-down policy.


395
00:57:54.564 --> 00:58:02.624
Incoming livestream: So nobody installs packages that are less than 7 days old. For any package manager across the company, we have it enforced with MDM.


396
00:58:03.884 --> 00:58:20.524
Incoming livestream: That's the, I think, the easiest way to reduce risk and make the safe path the default path. There's more that we've done here, but this is something that I'm preparing to release. We're gonna start open sourcing our entire, Jamf configuration stack for how we secure some of these agents with MDM.


397
00:58:22.004 --> 00:58:32.644
Incoming livestream: And then finally, once you have the policies, the guardrails, the sandboxes, the skills, you can connect agents to real tools. So one example that we've already wrapped inside of an MCP server is Slither.


398
00:58:32.644 --> 00:58:44.403
Incoming livestream: And if you don't care about Slither, which is a static analyzer for Ethereum smart contracts, the point is that MCP turns your internal tools into something that agents can use reliably, and that your org can govern.


399
00:58:45.254 --> 00:58:50.084
Incoming livestream: So this is another way that we can inject policy into how these tools get used.


400
00:58:51.344 --> 00:59:09.354
Incoming livestream: So now the results. So, you know, you've seen some of our open source work, but internally, I can share that we have 94 separate plugins accumulating 201 skills, with 84 specialized agents and 400 reference files, encoding all of our domain expertise.


401
00:59:09.544 --> 00:59:16.263
Incoming livestream: And that's the compounding effect. So every single engagement, every auditor, every experiment adds to that arsenal.


402
00:59:16.394 --> 00:59:26.904
Incoming livestream: And what's important is the breadth, right? We're not just talking about an auditing toolkit. I have skills for writing sales proposals, tracking project hours, onboarding new hires, prepping conference blog posts.


403
00:59:27.114 --> 00:59:44.494
Incoming livestream: We have 20-plus plugin… plugins targeting specific vulnerability classes, but, you know, each… the important thing is each package, each one packages expertise that used to live in somebody's head, and it turns into something that every auditor on the team can now invoke.


404
00:59:44.794 --> 00:59:46.353
Incoming livestream: On the delivery side.


405
00:59:46.514 --> 00:59:55.494
Incoming livestream: We have certain clients where the codebase and the scope allow it. We've gone from finding 15 bugs a week to finding 200 bugs per week.


406
00:59:55.874 --> 01:00:06.593
Incoming livestream: And that's not a faster human. That's an auditor running a fleet of specialized engagements that do targeted analysis across the codebase in parallel, and then validate the results.


407
01:00:06.934 --> 01:00:17.724
Incoming livestream: So, across most of our engagements at Trail of Bits, the number that we're about at is that 20% of all the bugs we report to our clients were initially discovered by AI.


408
01:00:18.384 --> 01:00:28.124
Incoming livestream: On the business side, we also have our sales team averaging about $8 million in revenue per representative, which is about double what the industry averages for,


409
01:00:28.344 --> 01:00:30.523
Incoming livestream: For sales, for sales consulting.


410
01:00:30.864 --> 01:00:44.113
Incoming livestream: So, yeah, so AI doesn't just help our engineers, it also helps with proposal drafting, competitive positioning, conference prep, lead enrichment, same system, same repositories, same compounding effect.


411
01:00:45.024 --> 01:00:52.984
Incoming livestream: And this is maybe, you know, a year into building this system seriously. Cloud Code came out, what was it, about a year ago.


412
01:00:53.194 --> 01:00:59.903
Incoming livestream: The models get better every month, the skills grow every week, and a year from now, these numbers are gonna look very different.


413
01:01:03.994 --> 01:01:18.614
Incoming livestream: So, let me close with some of the essential starter path. This is the minimum viable AI-native org design. This is what we've done so far, and it's changed how fast we can ship and how quickly we adapt. If you want to copy this, you have to copy the system, not the tools.


414
01:01:19.363 --> 01:01:23.404
Incoming livestream: We do have some open questions, you know, there's obviously some things we're still working on.


415
01:01:24.774 --> 01:01:33.093
Incoming livestream: Obviously, Gotti made an allusion to a conversation I had with him about private inference. You know, we don't want to always send our…


416
01:01:33.134 --> 01:01:49.993
Incoming livestream: queries to the cloud. Sometimes we want to do them on a machine that we control. But, these local models, they're good, but they're not amazing. There's definitely this big model smell where you can tell the difference between, you know, Opus 4.6 and a Haiku 4.6, no matter what day it is.


417
01:01:50.174 --> 01:02:06.584
Incoming livestream: So right now, we're investigating a couple of paths here, and I'm sort of reticent to spend money on a local server, because a lot of the private inference systems are getting really good. We've been evaluating tinfoil.sh, but there's a huge variety of other private inference servers that are now available, where I can


418
01:02:07.213 --> 01:02:10.463
Incoming livestream: Confidentially run my queries in somebody else's cloud.


419
01:02:10.953 --> 01:02:15.623
Incoming livestream: So these are where, you know, we're doing some research to figure out the right solution for us.


420
01:02:15.734 --> 01:02:30.253
Incoming livestream: The prompt injection problem? Obviously not solved. We have a real blunt instrument for solving it today, which is for certain clients, we just deny access to the web. And for a lot of our internal tools, we don't allow them access to external resources.


