601
01:28:37.524 --> 01:28:56.174
Incoming livestream: So, in this talk, the AI vulnerability research components we will focus on are reverse engineering and fuzzing. Reverse engineering is inferring how a compiled system works from binaries and runtime behavior, while fuzzing is automatically generating and mutating inputs to exercise system and surface bugs via crashes or violated invariants.


602
01:28:56.394 --> 01:29:14.034
Incoming livestream: My workload tries to automate steps in these areas that I've found to be most reliable. First, the AI workflow treats Apple's open source code as a sensor, and a sensor is any data source that produces signals about a system or state change without doing interpretation for you.


603
01:29:14.034 --> 01:29:23.613
Incoming livestream: Second, the workload then uses AI agents to turn that sensor into a prioritized queue. So what changed, what looked security relevant, what to reverse, and what to fuzz.


604
01:29:23.614 --> 01:29:29.463
