644
01:36:37.384 --> 01:36:43.184
Incoming livestream: I don't treat the model as God, I treat it as a junior-junior engineer that can read,


645
01:36:43.434 --> 01:36:49.254
Incoming livestream: Fast, follow procedures, and generate structured hypotheses that we can validate with reversing, tracing, and fuzzing.


646
01:36:49.394 --> 01:37:00.834
Incoming livestream: Additionally, it's important to remember that each step in itself can break, and that they're all depending on each other. Thus, your setup should ideally account for that since you might be on a paid personal plan with limited resources.


647
01:37:01.714 --> 01:37:08.304
Incoming livestream: The big addition to this talk versus, like, the classic, I used Apple OSS to reverse stuff, is logs.


648
01:37:08.544 --> 01:37:24.473
Incoming livestream: Unified logging gives you subsystem and category labels that map back to components, stable message releases, and strings that can, help you hunt in binaries and source, as well as execution hints that you can use to reconstruct data flow diagrams without the full source.


649
01:37:24.824 --> 01:37:38.574
Incoming livestream: I treat unified logs as a pivot into attack surface and code paths, not as, like, a doctrine because of how noisy and bulky these logs are, and I don't always know how to handle that. They're good at telling you which components actually handled the output.


650
01:37:38.704 --> 01:37:52.594
Incoming livestream: Or input, so, like, things like, subsystem or category plus sender image info, and then what error paths fired that can reveal, like, parsing assumptions, type expectations, and, IPC contracts.


651
01:37:53.044 --> 01:37:57.963
Incoming livestream: And that's pretty good ROI for target selection, harness design, and what to fuzz next.


652
01:37:58.504 --> 01:38:03.613
Incoming livestream: An AI agent, in general, can do, like, 3 useful bounded tasks with logs.


653
01:38:03.614 --> 01:38:18.684
Incoming livestream: First, it can take a log line and find where that string lives in a binary via strings, and then locate its basic block and callers. Next, it can retrieve adjacent OSS code for those callers if it exists, and produce a structured summary, like inputs, trust boundaries, and parsing.


654
01:38:18.804 --> 01:38:30.134
Incoming livestream: Lastly, it can feed that summary into fuzz planning, or, like, into detection engineering, like what to watch, what parameters are attacker controlled, and then what failure modes might look like.


655
01:38:31.004 --> 01:38:43.064
Incoming livestream: And this is relevant to developing POCs as well as, like, localized endpoint tests or detections. So, when your privileged AI pipeline learns a new untrusted input boundary or a new privileged XBC entry point.


656
01:38:43.064 --> 01:38:52.993
Incoming livestream: You can translate it into telemetry requirements and correlation rules. And in general, that's how you turn vulnerability research into coverage. Only in the past, we did it manually.


657
01:38:53.084 --> 01:39:05.514
Incoming livestream: The same idea applies to those, like, back-in-the-day kernel extensions. By diffing KX across versions, researchers have found changes to external method tables that surface new or patched entry points in IO kit drivers.


658
01:39:05.614 --> 01:39:13.374
Incoming livestream: And, what this, fuzz Planner agent produces is not an exploit, unless, like, you made it do that somehow, it's a plan.


659
01:39:13.414 --> 01:39:26.914
Incoming livestream: First, it enumerates candidate services like syscall handlers, IO kit, user clients, XPC services, and parsers that you focus on the entry points where attacker-controlled inputs actually cross trust boundaries.


660
01:39:27.054 --> 01:39:40.064
Incoming livestream: Then, it produces a minimal test harness, like a test driver, including the invocation path, the entitlement requirements, and the expected input shape so that the target is actually reachable and reproducible at scale.


661
01:39:40.294 --> 01:39:51.263
Incoming livestream: Next, the AI recommends a seed strategy by extracting dictionaries from strings, mining parameters from logs, or bootstrapping from observed traffic so that the coverage ramps quickly instead of mutating from nothing.


662
01:39:52.024 --> 01:40:09.724
Incoming livestream: Note that if the command is not available in the subset that I provided, you can add them yourself or connect an AI search chatbot so that it can find them automatically. I don't necessarily recommend just, like, allowing your laptop to just, like, run whatever you want and Google whatever you want and just, like, go ham.


663
01:40:09.864 --> 01:40:15.544
Incoming livestream: But if you have test MacBooks and all that stuff, go ahead and do that, because it can be cool.


664
01:40:15.934 --> 01:40:27.843
Incoming livestream: Also, like, the seed strategy part is the method for selecting and generating the initial set of representative inputs that bootstraps a buzzer's coverage and guides the mutations towards a high-value code path.


665
01:40:28.334 --> 01:40:40.163
Incoming livestream: Finally, the AI defined success metrics, like crash bucketing, sanitizer signals, and unique stack traces so that you can identify progress and, you know, ideally turn these results into actionable research.


666
01:40:41.054 --> 01:40:46.633
Incoming livestream: Where this AI workflow breaks down today is when you ask for full chain exploits.


667
01:40:47.044 --> 01:41:04.204
Incoming livestream: To be honest, I'm not at the point in my research career where I am finding full privilege escalations and, like, disabling all the macOS security controls. Additionally, I've spent significant time just trying to understand and test how the operating system is working, and this knowledge is great for that learning-by-doing approach, too.


668
01:41:04.334 --> 01:41:10.214
Incoming livestream: That said, these models will occasionally invent steps, especially if you hook up an AI chatbot.


669
01:41:10.254 --> 01:41:28.874
Incoming livestream: And so I try to keep it as constrained as possible due to the nature of how large these subsystems are, and how much information I am sending, and how much money it takes to process all of that information. So, the constraints I put on it are, like, bug class prediction and harness design, those are the high-value outputs, and then humans own the exploitability.


670
01:41:28.934 --> 01:41:38.464
Incoming livestream: This also keeps the larger AI models, which is primarily what I use, happy, given that a lot of them try to put mechanisms to lock them down for offensive research purposes.


671
01:41:38.494 --> 01:41:57.704
Incoming livestream: And if you're like me and don't fully trust your first past instincts, it helps to sanity check, like, your ideas on what to exploit against high-quality public works. For example, Patrick Wordle has an extensive body of writing, and I use AI tooling to check whether or not my hypotheses line up with established techniques in his published analysis, as well as my own notes.


672
01:41:57.704 --> 01:42:03.303
Incoming livestream: This isn't wired into the OSS project yet, but I might add it since I do these sanity checks quite frequently.


673
01:42:03.474 --> 01:42:15.374
Incoming livestream: Also, credit where it's due, I intentionally licensed OSS Sensor as GPLv3, because I learned a lot from GPLv3 licensed work by Patrick and many others, and keeping that code shareable helps others build and learn in the same way.


674
01:42:15.504 --> 01:42:24.923
Incoming livestream: So, the TLDR is that even partial source is powerful, combine it with binary analysis, and you can reverse Apple subsystems with surprising accuracy.


675
01:42:24.924 --> 01:42:40.663
Incoming livestream: But there are constraints, which is that, you know, incomplete OSS releases, obfuscation, and licensing. You need a pipeline that is compliant by design with, like, the local indexing, careful handling of source drops, and provenance tracking, so that you can explain every conclusion.


676
01:42:41.434 --> 01:42:48.843
Incoming livestream: All of that said, what did we learn? The core idea I want to leave you with is that Apple's partial open source can be treated as a sensor stream.


677
01:42:48.864 --> 01:43:04.744
Incoming livestream: It's not the full system, but it's a steady source of change signals, and those signals become much more valuable when you can process them continuously. The workflow I showed takes that sensor and turns it into a prioritized research queue using AI agents, but with a very specific philosophy.


678
01:43:04.774 --> 01:43:08.364
Incoming livestream: The model's not God, it's a tool using Juno Annualist.


679
01:43:09.004 --> 01:43:25.053
Incoming livestream: This… the work, happens in deterministic tooling, and the model's job is to stitch together the evidence, retrieve the right context, and produce structured outputs that make a human faster and more consistent. That's why the narrative is diff to hypothesis to harness.


680
01:43:25.634 --> 01:43:41.604
Incoming livestream: You start with a diff, source or binary, you ask what meaningfully changed, and where the trust boundaries might be. Then you turn that into a testable hypothesis about a bug class. It can help with size calculation issues, parsing assumptions, policy gating, and interface surface shift.


681
01:43:41.804 --> 01:43:49.404
Incoming livestream: Then, you build a minimal test driver so that the path is reachable and reproducible, which sets you up for fuzzing and for validation.


682
01:43:49.424 --> 01:44:06.933
Incoming livestream: The trick is that the open source diff alone is not enough. We need to augment it with two other signals, the binaries, because they reflect the reality of what ships, and then the OS logs, because unified logging is a good ROI pivot point, and two, which components actually handled that input, and which error paths fired.


683
01:44:07.464 --> 01:44:25.153
Incoming livestream: The Fuzz Planner piece is an example of how this stays, like, practical and bounded. It doesn't generate an exploit, it generates a plan, and it tells you which surfaces matter, how to quickly reach them with a minimal harness, how to seat inputs so that coverage ramps quickly, and then how to measure the results so that you can identify findings.


684
01:44:25.284 --> 01:44:37.724
Incoming livestream: And importantly, it acknowledges the limits. Open source releases are incomplete, binaries can be opaque, and models can hallucinate. And that's why everything is evidence-backed, Providence-tracked, and compliant by design.


